2. These mechanisms interact such that if the opponent contributed more (a higher token_opp relative to token_self), the proposer may view it as fair to award a higher percentage to the opponent, and vice versa.
3. A simple mathematical form is a linear model that weights the normalized difference (token_opp minus token_self normalized by their sum) and adds an intercept that captures a baseline fairness standard (often around 50%). This formulation ensures that when contributions are equal the predicted proposed percentage defaults to the intercept.
4. Accordingly, two learnable parameters are defined: one for the intercept (baseline fairness) and one for sensitivity to the normalized token difference.
5. The model directly maps to observable behavior by predicting "proposed_perc" from token_self and token_opp. The formula guarantees that our model uses only the provided dataset structure and the learnable parameters have generous yet finite bounds to reduce covariance issues.

